# PowerShell Syntax Guidelines

## Windows Environment
This project runs on Windows with PowerShell as the default shell. Always use proper PowerShell syntax and commands.

## Common PowerShell Commands

### Directory Operations
```powershell
# Create directory
New-Item -ItemType Directory -Path "path/to/directory"
# or
mkdir directory-name

# List directory contents
Get-ChildItem
# or
ls

# Change directory
Set-Location "path"
# or
cd "path"
```

### File Operations
```powershell
# Create file
New-Item -ItemType File -Path "filename.txt"
# or
echo $null > filename.txt

# Copy file
Copy-Item "source.txt" "destination.txt"
# or
cp "source.txt" "destination.txt"

# Move file
Move-Item "source.txt" "destination.txt"
# or
mv "source.txt" "destination.txt"

# Remove file
Remove-Item "filename.txt"
# or
rm "filename.txt"
```

### Environment Variables
```powershell
# Set environment variable
$env:VARIABLE_NAME = "value"

# Get environment variable
$env:VARIABLE_NAME

# Check if variable exists
if ($env:VARIABLE_NAME) { "Variable exists" }
```

### Node.js/NPM Commands
```powershell
# Install dependencies
npm install

# Run scripts
npm run dev
npm run build
npm run db:push

# Run with specific Node version
npx tsx scripts/seed.ts
```

### Database Commands
```powershell
# Prisma commands
npx prisma db push
npx prisma generate
npx prisma studio
npx prisma migrate dev
```

## Path Handling
- Use forward slashes `/` in paths when possible (PowerShell handles both)
- Use quotes around paths with spaces: `"C:\Program Files\Node.js"`
- Use `$PWD` for current working directory
- Use `~` for user home directory

## Error Handling
```powershell
# Check if command succeeded
if ($LASTEXITCODE -eq 0) {
    Write-Host "Command succeeded" -ForegroundColor Green
} else {
    Write-Host "Command failed" -ForegroundColor Red
}
```

## Common Patterns
- Use `Write-Host` instead of `echo` for colored output
- Use `-Force` flag to overwrite existing files
- Use `-Recurse` flag for recursive operations
- Use `-ErrorAction SilentlyContinue` to suppress errors